      <div class="decisions-list fade-up fade-up-d2">
        <div style="font-size:0.78rem; font-weight:700; color:var(--mum-pink); letter-spacing:1px; text-transform:uppercase; margin-bottom:16px;">Design Decisions & Tradeoffs</div>
        <div class="decision-card">
          <h4>RAG-lite vs Full Vector Database</h4>
          <p>Keyword + tag matching chosen for speed, debuggability, and zero external dependencies. Perfectly suited for well-defined product domains.</p>
          <div class="decision-pros-cons">
            <div class="pros"><strong>✅ Pros</strong>Fast, controllable, no embedding cost, easy to swap with vector DB in production</div>
            <div class="cons"><strong>⚠️ Tradeoff</strong>Less flexible for semantic similarity — mitigated by structured product tags</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="decision-card">
          <h4>Synthetic Product Dataset</h4>
          <p>Handcrafted dataset instead of real catalog. Focus on demonstrating the pipeline architecture — real catalog is a one-line swap in production.</p>
          <div class="decision-pros-cons">
            <div class="pros"><strong>✅ Pros</strong>Proves the architecture without API dependency. System is catalog-agnostic.</div>
            <div class="cons"><strong>⚠️ Tradeoff</strong>Smaller dataset limits retrieval variety — fixed by connecting real Mumzworld API</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="decision-card">
          <h4>OpenRouter over Direct API</h4>
          <p>Single API key, model-agnostic, cost-effective for prototyping. Swap to direct Anthropic or OpenAI calls for production with zero code changes.</p>
          <div class="decision-pros-cons">
            <div class="pros"><strong>✅ Pros</strong>Any model in one interface — tested with Claude 3.5 Sonnet for best results</div>
            <div class="cons"><strong>⚠️ Tradeoff</strong>Additional network hop — acceptable for demo, remove for low-latency production</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

